Preheat your #oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Remove the @puff pastry sheet{3/4} from your fridge.

Bring a large #saucepan of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil. Peel and slice the @potatoes{450} into 1cm thick rounds.

Once boiling, add the potato slices to the water and simmer until just tender, ~{8-12%minutes}.

Once cooked, reserve some of the @reserved potato water{75%ml}, then carefully drain in a #colander.

Meanwhile, trim the root and the dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways, then thinly slice. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan on medium heat.

Once hot, add the leek and @British smoked bacon lardons{90%g} and cook until golden, ~{4-6%minutes}, stirring occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Cook lardons thoroughly.

Stir half the garlic into the leek and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add the @creme fraiche{150%g}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, reserved potato water and @grated hard Italian style cheese{25%g}. Mix together, bring to the boil, then remove from the heat.

Stir in the @crumbled blue cheese{30%g} until smooth, then season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Lay the cooked potato slices in layers in an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}, then pour over the creamy sauce. Carefully bang the dish on a hard surface to remove air bubbles.

Cover with the puff pastry, trimming off any excess. Press some over the side of the dish if you can, or just sit it on top. Make a small hole in the middle - this allows the steam to escape.

> TIP: Brush the pastry with a little milk if you have some.

Bake on the top shelf of your #oven until golden brown and bubbly, ~{20-25%minutes}.

> TIP: Put the dish onto a #baking tray{} to catch any drips.

Meanwhile, clean your #frying pan and trim the @green beans{150%g}.

When the pie has ~{10%minutes} left, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in the #frying pan on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the green beans and stir-fry until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in the remaining garlic, then turn the heat down to medium and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add a splash of @water{} and immediately cover with a #lid or some #foil. Allow to cook until the beans are tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove from the heat.

Once cooked, serve your dauphinoise pie with the garlicky green beans alongside.

Enjoy!